	volume = {106},
	issn = {0090-0656},
	shorttitle = {All their eggs in one basket},
	url = {http://hdl.handle.net/1834/25476},
	abstract = {Skates (family Rajidae) are oviparous and lay tough, thick-walled eggs. At least some skate species lay their eggs in spatially restricted nursery grounds where embryos develop and hatch (Hitz, 1964; Hoff, 2007). After hatching, neonates may quickly leave the nursery grounds (Hoff, 2007). Egg densities in these small areas may be quite high. As an example, in the eastern Bering Sea, a site {\textless}2 km2 harbored eggs of Alaska skate (Bathyraja parmifera) exceeding 500,000/km2. All skate nursery grounds have beenidentified over soft sea floors (Lucifora and García, 2004; Hoff, 2007).},
